BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/ca3314f0-f716-4500-81fe-02298d394d2c.jpg
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260515T101925Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a walkthrough of the herbal gardens at the National Centre for Biological Sciences (NCBS) campus - a serene green spot nestled between a maze of labs\, and beloved by students\, staff\, faculty\, and resident cats alike.\n\nIts roots trace to a ground breaking exhibit in 2008 where former cell biologist and scholar of Indian botanical-medicinal traditions\, Annamma Spudich\, brought 50 medicinal plants described in the Hortus Malabaricus and planted a living exhibition in its spot. This exhibition\, titled "Such Treasure and Rich Merchandize: Indian Botanical knowledge in 16th and 17th Century European Books"\, was not only a unique collaboration between horticulturalists\, artists\, and historians\, but also one of the many growing efforts by the institution\, to reflect on history and society.\n\nAlmost two decades later\, the garden thrives\, but how much of a curation remains? And how have those initial ideas grown? Discover its story and learn about the Archives at NCBS and their work to document contemporary botanical records amongst its larger catalogue of history of science.\n\nThis programme is in collaboration with NCBS\, and in conjunction with MAP's ongoing exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire.
DTEND:20260530T080000Z
DTSTART:20260530T053000Z
SUMMARY:Such Treasure Revived: A Garden Walk and Visit to the Archives
UID:1278@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/such-treasure-revived-a-garden-walk-and-visit-to-the-archives/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/image.jpeg
CATEGORIES:Performances,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260522T114141Z
DESCRIPTION:Blending storytelling\, drag performance\, dance\, and multimedia elements\, the program traces KaMani Sutra’s journey of discovering femininity while navigating life as an adult immigrant in the United States.\n\nRooted in the richness of Indian drag aesthetics and cultural influences\, this artist's showcase reflects on identity\, migration\, and self-expression\, contrasting the freedom of living authentically in a foreign land with the complexities of belonging and visibility. Through short performances\, video\, and consensual audience participation\, the lecture-performance-artist showcase challenges ideas around the model minority myth\, binary gender\, and colonial saviorship.\n\nAt once celebratory and reflective\, the program honours intergenerational queerness\, LGBTQ+ community\, saris\, mujras\, divine femininity\, and the transformative power of self-love.\n\nThis programme is part of LGBTQIA+ programming and is an attempt to amplify narratives from within the queer community through film\, dialogue\, and collective reflection.
DTEND:20260607T140000Z
DTSTART:20260607T123000Z
SUMMARY:Being Queen is My Resistance: Lessons in Drag Mythology and Migration
UID:1294@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/being-queen-is-my-resistance-lessons-in-drag-mythology-and-migration/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/PTG.01769-e1779445722719.webp
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260522T113620Z
DESCRIPTION:Beneath the Turning Sky explores how we find our place in this world. How have our choices shaped what we are left with today\, and what are the weighty myths\, stories and headlines that trace our endless attempts to understand the cosmos?\n\nIn this workshop\, participants will be given a peer-led walkthrough of Beneath the Turning Sky by Job\, one of our Teen Takeover participants\, following which they will be required to research and act out various time periods covered within the exhibition and depict the cycles of wonder\, destruction\, exploitation and creation.  \n\nThrough this exercise\, the hope is to help us understand the vicious cycles that we are stuck in and how to break out of them and imagine more hopeful futures.\n\nThis programme is hosted in conjunction with the Teen Takeover programme.
DTEND:20260606T103000Z
DTSTART:20260606T093000Z
SUMMARY:What the Sky Sees
UID:1291@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/what-the-sky-sees/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/image-2.png
CATEGORIES:Online Talk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260527T070119Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Voyage to Calicut Series\, Tapestry\, Silk and Wool\, 1504\, Portuguese National Library\, Lisbon\nFor centuries India was the nexus of a global trade in spices\, medicines\, dyes\, unguents and perfumes—high‑value goods whose value rested on deep\, native knowledge of plants and healing. In this online talk\, renowned researcher Dr. Annamma Spudich traces how archaeological finds and trade records from the first millennium onwards reveal India’s sophisticated botanical and medical systems\, and why by the Middle Ages “India trade was the backbone of the international economy.”\n\nLearn how the late‑15th‑century European search for direct sea routes brought Spain\, Portugal\, and later the Dutch and British\, into India\, and how\, finding their own medical knowledge inadequate for the tropics\, turned to Indian physicians and botanical expertise. Dr Spudich will examine these European documents from the 16th–19th centuries that recorded Indian medicinal\, agricultural and horticultural knowledge\, and show how these encounters broadened Western science\, inspired artists and poets and reshaped global history.\n\nThis online talk is in conjunction with MAP’s ongoing exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire\, bringing together over a hundred botanical illustrations\, tracing encounters between plants\, artists\, and institutions\, and reanimating the networks of labour and imagination that have built our understanding of the natural world.
DTEND:20260531T150000Z
DTSTART:20260531T140000Z
SUMMARY:In Search of Knowledge and Riches
UID:1287@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/in-search-for-knowledge-and-riches/
END:VEVENT
